

= Infrastructure Due Diligence Analyst Role

== Private Markets (Infrastructure) Manager - Investment Team

== Overview

Infrastructure Due Diligence Analysts at private markets managers play a critical role in evaluating potential infrastructure investments, conducting rigorous financial, commercial, and technical analysis to inform investment decisions. Unlike equity research analysts who assess publicly traded companies, infrastructure analysts evaluate long-lived physical assets (airports, toll roads, energy infrastructure, utilities, digital infrastructure) with complex regulatory frameworks, contracted cash flows, and 20-50+ year investment horizons.

In Australia, major infrastructure investors include IFM Investors, AustralianSuper (Direct Infrastructure team), QIC, First Sentier Investors, and international managers like Macquarie Asset Management, Brookfield, and AMP Capital (now Dexus). These firms deploy capital across core infrastructure (stable, regulated assets like energy networks and water utilities), core-plus infrastructure (moderate growth assets like airports and toll roads), and value-add infrastructure (higher-risk development or operational turnaround opportunities).

Infrastructure due diligence requires a unique skill set combining financial modeling, engineering/technical understanding, regulatory analysis, and commercial judgment. Analysts must assess traffic forecasts, energy demand projections, regulatory reset methodologies, competitive dynamics, and ESG considerations while building sophisticated discounted cash flow models spanning decades.

This document outlines the Infrastructure Due Diligence Analyst role, focusing on the analytical foundation of infrastructure investing and the pathway from graduate analyst to experienced investment professional.

